          "title": "Modality Representations & Embeddings",
          "slug": "modality-representations",
          "order_index": 1,
          "content": "# Modality Representations & Embeddings\n\n## The Encoding Problem\n\nBefore different modalities can be fused, each must be converted into a format neural networks can process \u2014 dense vector representations. The quality of these **encoders** directly determines the quality of the multi-modal model built on top of them.\n\n## Vision Encoders\n\n**CNNs to ViTs**: Early multi-modal models used CNN backbones (ResNet, EfficientNet) to extract image features. Modern systems use **Vision Transformers (ViTs)**, which split images into fixed-size patches (typically 14\u00d714 or 16\u00d716 pixels), flatten each patch into a vector, and process them through Transformer layers \u2014 treating an image as a \"sequence of patches.\"\n\n```python\n# ViT: Image \u2192 patch embeddings\npatches = image.reshape(B, num_patches, patch_dim)  # (B, 196, 768) for ViT-B/16\npatch_embeddings = linear_projection(patches)\n# Add positional embeddings, then process through Transformer layers\n```\n\nThe key insight: ViTs produce a **sequence of patch representations** \u2014 one vector per image region \u2014 which naturally interfaces with language models through cross-attention.\n\n**SigLIP** and **DINOv2** are popular open-source vision encoders. SigLIP is trained contrastively with text (like CLIP), while DINOv2 learns visual features through self-supervised learning without any text at all.\n\n## Audio Encoders\n\nAudio is typically converted to a **mel spectrogram** \u2014 a 2D time-frequency representation \u2014 which can then be processed like an image:\n\n```python\nimport torchaudio.transforms as T\nmel_spec = T.MelSpectrogram(sample_rate=16000, n_mels=80)(waveform)\n# Shape: (1, 80, time_steps) \u2014 can be processed by CNN or ViT\n```\n\nWhisper uses a CNN-based encoder on mel spectrograms. Newer models like **wav2vec 2.0** and **HuBERT** learn directly from raw waveforms using self-supervised pre-training, producing discrete audio tokens that can be processed like text.\n\n## Text Encoders\n\nText encoding is handled by the tokenization and embedding layers covered in the LLM course. In multi-modal models, the text encoder is often a pre-trained LLM (Llama, Vicuna) or a CLIP text encoder, depending on whether the model needs generative language capabilities or just text understanding.\n\n## Shared Embedding Spaces\n\nThe breakthrough insight of CLIP was training vision and text encoders **jointly** so their outputs land in the same vector space. After training, you can directly compare a text embedding with an image embedding using cosine similarity:\n\n```python\nimage_features = vision_encoder(image)     # (B, d)\ntext_features = text_encoder(text)         # (B, d)\nsimilarity = (image_features @ text_features.T)  # cosine similarity\n```\n\nThis shared space enables zero-shot classification, image-text retrieval, and serves as the foundation for vision-language models.\n\n## Projection Layers\n\nWhen connecting a pre-trained vision encoder to a pre-trained LLM, a **projection layer** (often a simple MLP) maps vision embeddings into the LLM's input space:\n\n```python\nclass ModalityProjection(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, vision_dim, llm_dim):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.proj = nn.Sequential(\n            nn.Linear(vision_dim, llm_dim),\n            nn.GELU(),\n            nn.Linear(llm_dim, llm_dim)\n        )\n    def forward(self, x):\n        return self.proj(x)\n```\n\nLLaVA uses this pattern: ViT encoder \u2192 MLP projection \u2192 Llama LLM. The projection is often the only component trained from scratch \u2014 everything else is pre-trained.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [An Image is Worth 16x16 Words: Transformers for Image Recognition at Scale](https://arxiv.org/abs/2010.11929) (Dosovitskiy et al., 2020) \u2014 the original Vision Transformer (ViT) paper that showed patches + Transformers match or beat CNNs.\n",
          "summary": "Each modality requires specialized encoders \u2014 Vision Transformers for images, mel spectrograms for audio \u2014 and projection layers bridge them into shared embedding spaces.",
          "concepts": [
            "Vision Transformer",
