          "title": "Contrastive Learning & CLIP",
          "slug": "contrastive-learning-clip",
          "order_index": 0,
          "content": "# Contrastive Learning & CLIP\n\n## The Intuition: Learning by Comparison\n\n**Contrastive learning** doesn't tell the model what an image \"is\" \u2014 instead, it teaches the model which images and texts go together and which don't. Given a batch of image-text pairs, the model learns to pull matching pairs close together in embedding space while pushing non-matching pairs apart.\n\nThis is fundamentally different from supervised classification (which needs labeled categories) or generative pre-training (which predicts the next token). Contrastive learning needs only paired data \u2014 images with their captions \u2014 which exists at massive scale on the internet.\n\n## CLIP: Contrastive Language-Image Pre-training\n\n**CLIP** (Radford et al., 2021) trained a dual-encoder architecture on **400 million image-text pairs** scraped from the web:\n\n```\nImage Encoder (ViT)  \u2500\u2500\u25ba image embedding (d=512)\n                                                    \u2500\u2500\u25ba cosine similarity matrix\nText Encoder (Transformer) \u2500\u2500\u25ba text embedding (d=512)\n```\n\n### The Training Objective\n\nGiven a batch of N image-text pairs, CLIP computes an N\u00d7N similarity matrix. The diagonal contains matching pairs (positives); everything else is a negative:\n\n```python\nlogits = (image_features @ text_features.T) * temperature\nlabels = torch.arange(N)  # diagonal = correct pairs\nloss = (cross_entropy(logits, labels) +       # image \u2192 text\n        cross_entropy(logits.T, labels)) / 2  # text \u2192 image\n```\n\nThis **InfoNCE loss** maximizes the similarity of N correct pairs while minimizing similarity with N\u00b2\u2212N incorrect pairs. With a batch size of 32,768, each sample gets 32,767 negatives \u2014 a very strong training signal.\n\n## Zero-Shot Classification\n\nCLIP's killer feature: classify images into arbitrary categories **without any labeled training data**. Create text prompts for each class and pick the one with highest similarity:\n\n```python\nprompts = [f\"a photo of a {cls}\" for cls in imagenet_classes]\ntext_features = clip.encode_text(prompts)\nimage_features = clip.encode_image(image)\nprediction = (image_features @ text_features.T).argmax()\n```\n\nCLIP matched a fully supervised ResNet-50 on ImageNet \u2014 trained on zero ImageNet labels \u2014 by leveraging the massive diversity of its web-scraped training data.\n\n## Beyond CLIP\n\n**SigLIP** (Zhai et al., 2023) replaces the softmax-based InfoNCE loss with a simpler sigmoid loss applied to each pair independently, removing the need for global batch-level normalization and making training more efficient.\n\n**OpenCLIP** provides open-source reproductions trained on LAION-5B (5 billion image-text pairs), often exceeding OpenAI's original CLIP.\n\n## Why CLIP Changed Everything\n\nCLIP's impact extends far beyond image classification:\n\n- **Foundation for VLMs**: CLIP's vision encoder is used as the \"eyes\" for LLaVA, BLIP-2, and most vision-language models\n- **Image generation**: Stable Diffusion uses CLIP text embeddings to condition the diffusion process\n- **Zero-shot everything**: CLIP enables image search, content moderation, and retrieval without task-specific training\n- **The CLIP paradigm**: Training on web-scale paired data using contrastive objectives became the template for multi-modal foundation models\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [Learning Transferable Visual Models From Natural Language Supervision](https://arxiv.org/abs/2103.00020) (Radford et al., 2021) \u2014 the CLIP paper. The results section is genuinely surprising, showing zero-shot performance rivaling supervised models.\n",
          "summary": "CLIP uses contrastive learning to align image and text representations in a shared embedding space, enabling zero-shot classification and serving as the foundation for modern vision-language models.",
          "concepts": [
            "contrastive learning",
            "CLIP",
            "InfoNCE loss",
            "zero-shot classification",
            "dual encoder",
            "SigLIP",
            "OpenCLIP"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        },
        {
          "title": "Visual Instruction Tuning",
          "slug": "visual-instruction-tuning",
          "order_index": 1,
          "content": "# Visual Instruction Tuning\n\n## From Understanding to Conversation\n\nCLIP can match images to text, but it can't hold a conversation about an image. It can't answer \"What breed is this dog?\" or \"Is this intersection safe to cross?\" **Vision-Language Models (VLMs)** combine a visual encoder with a large language model, enabling open-ended visual understanding and generation.\n\n## The LLaVA Architecture\n\n**LLaVA** (Liu et al., 2023) demonstrated a surprisingly simple and effective recipe: take a pre-trained vision encoder, connect it to a pre-trained LLM, and fine-tune on visual instruction-following data.\n\n```\nImage \u2192 CLIP ViT-L \u2192 MLP Projection \u2192 [visual tokens]\n                                            \u2193\nUser text \u2192 Tokenizer \u2192 [text tokens] + [visual tokens] \u2192 LLM \u2192 Response\n```\n\nThe visual tokens are treated as additional input tokens to the LLM \u2014 the language model \"reads\" the image as if it were a sequence of words.\n\n### Two-Stage Training\n\n1. **Pre-training alignment**: Train only the projection MLP on 558K image-caption pairs. The vision encoder and LLM are frozen. This teaches the projection layer to translate visual features into the LLM's \"language.\"\n\n2. **Visual instruction tuning**: Fine-tune the projection MLP and the LLM on 150K instruction-following examples (e.g., \"Describe this image in detail\", \"What's unusual about this photo?\"). The vision encoder stays frozen.\n\n```python\n# Simplified LLaVA forward pass\nvisual_features = clip_encoder(image)           # (num_patches, vision_dim)\nvisual_tokens = projection_mlp(visual_features) # (num_patches, llm_dim)\ntext_tokens = tokenizer(prompt)\ninput_embeds = concat(visual_tokens, text_tokens)\nresponse = llm.generate(inputs_embeds=input_embeds)\n```\n\n## The Modern VLM Landscape\n\n| Model | Visual Encoder | LLM | Key Innovation |\n|-------|---------------|-----|----------------|\n| **GPT-4V/4o** | Proprietary | GPT-4 | Production-grade, natively multi-modal |\n| **LLaVA-1.5** | CLIP ViT-L | Vicuna-13B | Simple MLP projection, strong baseline |\n| **Qwen-VL** | ViT-G | Qwen-72B | High resolution, bounding box grounding |\n| **InternVL 2** | InternViT-6B | InternLM2 | 6B vision encoder, dynamic resolution |\n| **Llama 3.2 Vision** | ViT | Llama 3.2 | Cross-attention gated fusion |\n| **Phi-3-Vision** | CLIP ViT | Phi-3 | Compact (4.2B), surprisingly capable |\n\n## Capabilities\n\nModern VLMs can:\n- **Describe** images with rich detail and context\n- **Answer questions** requiring visual reasoning (\"How many red cars?\")\n- **Read text** in images (OCR) \u2014 receipts, signs, documents\n- **Ground** objects by generating bounding box coordinates\n- **Reason** about relationships, spatial layouts, and visual logic\n\n## Resolution Matters\n\nCLIP was originally trained at 224\u00d7224 pixels. Real-world images contain fine text, small objects, and details lost at that resolution. Modern VLMs address this with **dynamic resolution** \u2014 splitting high-resolution images into multiple tiles, encoding each separately, and concatenating the patch tokens. More visual tokens means better detail but longer context and slower inference \u2014 a fundamental tradeoff.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [Visual Instruction Tuning](https://arxiv.org/abs/2304.08485) (Liu et al., 2023) \u2014 the LLaVA paper. Refreshingly simple architecture that sparked the open VLM movement.\n",
          "summary": "Vision-Language Models like LLaVA connect pre-trained vision encoders to LLMs through projection layers, enabling open-ended visual question answering and instruction following.",
          "concepts": [
            "vision-language models",
            "LLaVA",
            "visual instruction tuning",
            "visual tokens",
            "GPT-4V",
            "dynamic resolution",
            "VLM"
          ],
