        {
          "title": "Cross-Attention & Fusion Architectures",
          "slug": "cross-attention-fusion",
          "order_index": 0,
          "content": "# Cross-Attention & Fusion Architectures\n\n## The Bridge Between Modalities\n\nHow do you get a language model to \"see\" an image? The core mechanism is **cross-attention** \u2014 the same attention mechanism from the LLM course, but with queries from one modality and keys/values from another:\n\n```python\n# Self-attention: Q, K, V all from the same modality\nQ, K, V = text @ W_Q, text @ W_K, text @ W_V\n\n# Cross-attention: Q from text, K/V from vision\nQ = text @ W_Q          # \"What am I looking for?\"\nK = vision @ W_K        # \"What visual information is available?\"\nV = vision @ W_V        # \"What visual content to retrieve?\"\noutput = softmax(Q @ K.T / sqrt(d)) @ V\n```\n\nCross-attention lets language tokens selectively attend to relevant image patches \u2014 when generating the word \"dog\", the model's attention peaks on the image region containing the dog.\n\n## Fusion Architecture Design Space\n\n| Architecture | Example | How It Works | Tradeoffs |\n|-------------|---------|-------------|----------|\n| **Dual encoder** | CLIP | Separate encoders, late similarity | Fast retrieval, no deep interaction |\n| **MLP projection** | LLaVA | Visual tokens concatenated with text | Simple, visual tokens consume context |\n| **Cross-attention layers** | Flamingo, Llama 3.2 V | Dedicated cross-attention between layers | Rich interaction, modular |\n| **Learned queries** | BLIP-2 Q-Former | Fixed learnable queries attend to vision | Efficient, fixed visual budget |\n| **Early fusion** | Gemini, Fuyu | Interleave modalities from the start | Maximum interaction, train from scratch |\n\n## BLIP-2's Q-Former\n\n**BLIP-2** (Li et al., 2023) introduced an elegant bottleneck: instead of passing all ~577 ViT patch tokens to the LLM, use a small set of **32 learnable query tokens** that attend to the visual features through cross-attention:\n\n```\nImage \u2192 ViT (frozen) \u2192 577 patch embeddings\n                              \u2193 (cross-attention)\n             32 learnable queries \u2192 Q-Former \u2192 32 visual tokens \u2192 LLM\n```\n\nThis compresses visual information by ~18\u00d7 while preserving the most relevant content. The Q-Former is trained to extract the visual features that matter most for language tasks.\n\n## Perceiver: Modality-Agnostic Architecture\n\n**Perceiver** (Jaegle et al., 2021) generalizes the Q-Former idea: use a fixed-size set of **latent vectors** that attend to inputs of any modality and any length. Whether the input is a 1080p video, an audio clip, or a point cloud, the architecture is the same \u2014 only the input projection changes.\n\nThis solves the quadratic cost of self-attention over long inputs (like video) by keeping the latent array small.\n\n## Gated Cross-Attention (Flamingo)\n\n**Flamingo** (Almasri et al., 2022) inserts cross-attention layers between existing frozen LLM layers, with a learned **gating parameter** initialized to zero:\n\n```\noutput = LLM_layer(x) + tanh(\u03b1) * CrossAttention(x, visual_features)\n```\n\nThe `tanh(\u03b1)` gate starts at zero, so the model initially behaves exactly like the original LLM. During training, the gate gradually opens to incorporate visual information \u2014 a smooth, stable training process that preserves the LLM's language capabilities.\n\nLlama 3.2 Vision uses a similar approach with gated cross-attention layers inserted at regular intervals.\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n- Cross-attention is the fundamental mechanism for connecting modalities \u2014 one modality queries another\n- Architecture choices trade off between efficiency (Q-Former's compression) and expressiveness (early fusion)\n- Gated fusion (Flamingo) enables gradual integration of new modalities without destabilizing pre-trained models\n- The trend is toward more efficient bridging \u2014 not all visual tokens are equally important\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [BLIP-2: Bootstrapping Language-Image Pre-training with Frozen Image Encoders and Large Language Models](https://arxiv.org/abs/2301.12597) (Li et al., 2023) \u2014 the Q-Former architecture that set the template for efficient vision-language bridging.\n",
          "summary": "Cross-attention enables modalities to selectively attend to each other, with architectures like Q-Former and gated fusion balancing efficiency and expressiveness.",
          "concepts": [
            "cross-attention",
            "Q-Former",
            "Perceiver",
            "gated cross-attention",
            "BLIP-2",
            "Flamingo",
            "fusion architectures"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        },
        {
          "title": "Multi-Modal Pre-training",
          "slug": "multimodal-pretraining",
          "order_index": 1,
          "content": "# Multi-Modal Pre-training\n\n## Training Models to See, Read, and Reason\n\nPre-training a multi-modal model means teaching it to understand and connect different types of data \u2014 before it's fine-tuned for any specific task. The pre-training objective, data mixture, and training strategy determine what the model can do.\n\n## Flamingo: Few-Shot Multi-Modal Learning\n\n**Flamingo** (DeepMind, 2022) was designed to handle interleaved sequences of images and text \u2014 like a conversation where someone drops in photos mid-discussion. Its key innovations:\n\n1. **Perceiver Resampler**: Compresses variable-length visual features into a fixed 64-token representation\n2. **Gated cross-attention**: Injects vision into a frozen language model at regular intervals\n3. **Interleaved training data**: Trained on web pages with images and text mixed naturally\n\nThe result: Flamingo can do few-shot visual question answering by showing it a few image-answer examples in context, achieving strong performance with just 4-32 examples \u2014 no gradient updates needed.\n\n## Gemini: Natively Multi-Modal\n\nWhile most models bolt vision onto an existing LLM, **Gemini** (Google DeepMind, 2023) was designed as multi-modal from the ground up. All modalities \u2014 text, images, audio, video \u2014 are processed through a single unified architecture from the start of pre-training.\n\nKey differences from the \"bridge\" approach:\n- No separate vision encoder that's frozen and projected \u2014 vision and language are trained jointly\n- Native audio and video understanding (not just images)\n- Can interleave generation across modalities\n\nThis \"natively multi-modal\" approach avoids the information bottleneck of projection layers but requires training from scratch on massive multi-modal datasets \u2014 feasible only for the largest labs.\n\n## Pre-training Objectives\n\n| Objective | How It Works | What It Teaches |\n|-----------|-------------|----------------|\n| **Contrastive** (CLIP) | Match image-text pairs | Alignment: same concept, same region |\n| **Image-text matching** | Binary: does this caption match? | Fine-grained alignment |\n| **Masked language modeling** | Predict masked text given image | Visual grounding of language |\n| **Image captioning** | Generate caption from image | Visual understanding, language generation |\n| **Next-token prediction** | Standard LLM objective on interleaved data | Unified multi-modal understanding |\n\nModern models increasingly use **next-token prediction on interleaved multi-modal sequences** as the primary objective \u2014 treating images, text, and audio as different types of tokens in a single stream.\n\n## Data: The Multi-Modal Web\n\nMulti-modal pre-training data comes from:\n\n| Source | Scale | Content |\n|--------|-------|--------|\n| **LAION-5B** | 5.8B image-text pairs | Web-scraped, noisy but massive |\n| **DataComp** | 1.4B curated pairs | Quality-filtered subset |\n| **Interleaved web** | Billions of pages | Images + surrounding text from web crawls |\n| **Video + transcripts** | Millions of hours | YouTube, instructional videos |\n| **Synthetic data** | Varies | LLM-generated captions, VQA pairs |\n\nData quality matters enormously \u2014 LAION-5B contains noise, duplicates, and problematic content. Significant engineering goes into filtering, deduplication, and safety classification.\n\n## The Convergence\n\nThe field is converging toward **unified multi-modal models** that handle all modalities natively. Rather than bolting modalities onto a text-only LLM, the next generation of foundation models will be multi-modal by default \u2014 understanding and generating text, images, audio, and video as naturally as today's LLMs handle text alone.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [Gemini: A Family of Highly Capable Multimodal Models](https://arxiv.org/abs/2312.11805) (Gemini Team, 2023) \u2014 the technical report for Gemini, showcasing natively multi-modal architecture and capabilities across text, image, audio, and video.\n",
          "summary": "Multi-modal pre-training teaches models to connect different data types through objectives like contrastive learning and next-token prediction on interleaved multi-modal sequences.",
          "concepts": [
            "multi-modal pre-training",
