        {
          "title": "Document Understanding & Multi-Modal RAG",
          "slug": "document-understanding-multimodal-rag",
          "order_index": 0,
          "content": "# Document Understanding & Multi-Modal RAG\n\n## Beyond Text-Only Retrieval\n\nStandard RAG pipelines (covered in the LLM course) retrieve text chunks and inject them into the prompt. But real-world documents contain **tables, charts, diagrams, equations, and complex layouts** that lose critical information when converted to plain text. Multi-modal RAG retrieves and reasons over documents as they actually appear \u2014 visually.\n\n## OCR-Free Document Understanding\n\nTraditional document processing pipelines extract text via OCR, then process it with an NLP model. This breaks tables, misreads formulas, and loses visual structure entirely. Modern document models skip OCR and process the rendered document image directly:\n\n| Model | Approach | Strengths |\n|-------|----------|----------|\n| **Donut** (Naver) | End-to-end image \u2192 text generation | No OCR needed, handles diverse formats |\n| **DocOwl** (Alibaba) | Document-focused VLM | Multi-page understanding |\n| **Nougat** (Meta) | Academic PDF \u2192 Markdown | LaTeX equations, paper structure |\n| **Florence-2** (Microsoft) | Unified vision model | OCR, captioning, detection, grounding |\n\nThese models understand that a number in a table header is semantically different from the same number in a footnote \u2014 something OCR-then-NLP pipelines struggle with.\n\n## ColPali: Visual Document Retrieval\n\n**ColPali** (Faysse et al., 2024) reimagined document retrieval by treating each page as an image:\n\n```\nTraditional: PDF \u2192 OCR \u2192 chunk text \u2192 embed chunks \u2192 search\nColPali:     PDF \u2192 render pages as images \u2192 embed patch tokens \u2192 search\n```\n\nColPali uses a vision-language model to produce **patch-level embeddings** for each document page. At query time, the text query is encoded, and a late-interaction mechanism compares query tokens against all patch tokens \u2014 finding the specific region of the page that answers the question.\n\nThe result: better retrieval on documents with complex layouts, tables, and figures, while being simpler (no OCR pipeline, no chunking decisions).\n\n## Multi-Modal RAG Pipelines\n\nA full multi-modal RAG system handles both text and visual content:\n\n```\nDocument Ingestion:\n  PDF pages \u2192 render as images\n            \u2192 extract text (optional, for hybrid search)\n            \u2192 generate visual embeddings (ColPali/CLIP)\n            \u2192 store in vector database (with images)\n\nRetrieval:\n  User query \u2192 embed query\n             \u2192 search visual + text embeddings\n             \u2192 re-rank combined results\n\nGeneration:\n  Retrieved pages (as images) + text chunks \u2192 VLM prompt\n  \u2192 Generate answer grounded in visual and textual evidence\n```\n\n## Structured Data Extraction\n\nA powerful application: extracting structured data from unstructured visual documents:\n\n```python\nprompt = \"\"\"Extract from this invoice image as JSON:\n- vendor_name (string)\n- invoice_date (YYYY-MM-DD)\n- line_items (array of {description, quantity, unit_price, total})\n- grand_total (number)\"\"\"\n\nresponse = vlm.generate(image=invoice_image, prompt=prompt)\ndata = json.loads(response)\n```\n\nVLMs can reliably extract data from invoices, receipts, forms, and tables \u2014 tasks that previously required custom OCR pipelines per document type.\n\n## Evaluation Challenges\n\nMulti-modal RAG evaluation is harder than text-only RAG:\n\n- **Retrieval**: Did the system find the right page/region? (Not just the right text chunk)\n- **Visual grounding**: Does the answer correctly reference visual elements?\n- **Layout understanding**: Can the system distinguish headers from content, footnotes from body text?\n- **Cross-page reasoning**: Can it synthesize information spread across multiple pages?\n\nBenchmarks like **DocVQA**, **InfographicsVQA**, and **MP-DocVQA** test these capabilities specifically.\n\n## Beyond Documents: Image & Video RAG\n\nDocument understanding is the most mature application, but multimodal RAG extends to any visual content:\n\n- **Image galleries**: Index product photos, architectural drawings, or medical scans with CLIP embeddings. Users search with natural language (\"red sneakers with white soles\") or with reference images (visual similarity search)\n- **Video libraries**: Split videos into keyframes, embed each frame, and retrieve specific moments. \"Find the slide where they discuss pricing\" across a library of recorded meetings\n- **Mixed knowledge bases**: Combine text documents, diagrams, screenshots, and videos in a single retrieval index. The query \"how does the authentication flow work?\" might retrieve a sequence diagram, a code snippet, and a documentation page \u2014 all as visual + text context for the VLM\n- **Multimodal memory for agents**: Agents that remember not just text conversations but screenshots, diagrams, and visual artifacts from past interactions \u2014 enabling truly context-aware assistance\n\nThe core pattern is the same: embed visual content alongside text, retrieve across both modalities, and generate answers grounded in the combined evidence.\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n- Real documents contain visual information that text-only RAG pipelines lose\n- ColPali and similar approaches embed document pages as images, enabling visual retrieval\n- Multi-modal RAG combines text and visual search for comprehensive document understanding\n- VLMs can extract structured data from unstructured visual documents without custom OCR\n",
          "summary": "Multi-modal RAG extends retrieval-augmented generation to handle visual documents \u2014 tables, charts, and complex layouts \u2014 through OCR-free models and visual document retrieval.",
          "concepts": [
            "multi-modal RAG",
            "ColPali",
            "OCR-free document understanding",
            "visual document retrieval",
            "DocVQA",
            "structured data extraction",
            "document AI",
            "cross-modal retrieval"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        },
        {
          "title": "Fine-Tuning Multi-Modal Models",
          "slug": "finetuning-multimodal-models",
          "order_index": 1,
          "content": "# Fine-Tuning Multi-Modal Models\n\n## When to Fine-Tune\n\nGeneral-purpose VLMs like LLaVA or Qwen-VL handle diverse tasks, but specialized domains \u2014 medical imaging, satellite analysis, manufacturing defect detection, document processing \u2014 require fine-tuning. The question is the same as for text LLMs: when does prompting fall short, and what's the most efficient way to adapt?\n\n## LoRA for Vision-Language Models\n\nLoRA (covered in the LLM course) applies directly to multi-modal models. The key decision is **which components to adapt**:\n\n```python\nfrom peft import LoraConfig, get_peft_model\n\nconfig = LoraConfig(\n    r=16,\n    lora_alpha=32,\n    target_modules=[\n        \"q_proj\", \"v_proj\",       # LLM attention\n        \"visual_proj\",            # Vision-language projection\n    ],\n    lora_dropout=0.05,\n)\nmodel = get_peft_model(vlm, config)\nmodel.print_trainable_parameters()\n```\n\n**Common strategies**:\n- **LLM only**: Fine-tune LoRA adapters on the language model, keep vision encoder frozen. Works well when your domain's visual features are similar to pre-training.\n- **LLM + projection**: Also adapt the projection layer. Better when the visual-semantic mapping needs adjustment.\n- **Full stack**: Adapt vision encoder + projection + LLM. Most expensive, needed for very different visual domains (e.g., X-rays, satellite imagery).\n\n## Data Preparation\n\nMulti-modal training data requires careful formatting:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"image\": \"path/to/image.jpg\",\n  \"conversations\": [\n    {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"<image>\\nWhat defect do you see?\"},\n    {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": \"The image shows a hairline crack along the die edge, approximately 2mm in length, consistent with thermal stress damage.\"}\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n**Data quality guidelines**:\n- **Diverse prompts**: Don't just ask \"describe this image\" \u2014 include questions, comparisons, counting, spatial reasoning\n- **Grounded answers**: Responses should reference specific visual details, not generic descriptions\n- **Negative examples**: Include cases where the correct answer is \"I don't see that\" or \"This image doesn't contain enough information\"\n- **Volume**: 1K-50K examples typically, depending on domain complexity\n\n## Compute Considerations\n\n| Configuration | GPU Memory | Typical Hardware |\n|---------------|-----------|------------------|\n| QLoRA (4-bit base) + LLM only | ~16 GB | Single RTX 4090 |\n| LoRA (16-bit) + LLM + projection | ~40 GB | Single A100 40GB |\n| Full fine-tune (7B VLM) | ~120 GB | 2-4\u00d7 A100 80GB |\n| Full fine-tune (70B+ VLM) | ~600 GB+ | 8+ A100/H100 |\n\nQLoRA makes domain adaptation accessible: fine-tune a 7B VLM on domain-specific data using a single consumer GPU.\n\n## Evaluation Approaches\n\nMulti-modal evaluation requires both automatic metrics and human review:\n\n**Automatic metrics**:\n- **VQA accuracy**: Exact or fuzzy match on visual question answering benchmarks\n- **CIDEr/METEOR**: Caption quality metrics (compare generated vs reference captions)\n- **GPT-4V as judge**: Use a stronger VLM to evaluate responses on rubrics\n\n**Domain-specific evaluation**:\n- **Medical**: Sensitivity/specificity on diagnosis tasks, comparison with expert radiologists\n- **Document**: Field extraction accuracy, table parsing correctness\n- **Manufacturing**: Defect detection precision/recall, false positive rates\n\n## Deployment Considerations\n\nDeploying multi-modal models adds complexity beyond text LLMs:\n\n- **Image preprocessing**: Consistent resizing, normalization, and tiling across training and inference\n- **Latency**: Vision encoding adds 50-200ms per image on top of LLM inference\n- **Bandwidth**: Sending images to a model API requires more bandwidth than text\n- **Caching**: Image embeddings can be pre-computed and cached for known documents\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [LLaVA-Med: Training a Large Language-and-Vision Assistant for Biomedicine](https://arxiv.org/abs/2306.00890) (Li et al., 2023) \u2014 a case study in domain-adapting a VLM for medical imaging, showing the fine-tuning pipeline from data curation through evaluation.\n",
          "summary": "Fine-tuning multi-modal models with LoRA/QLoRA adapts vision-language capabilities to specialized domains like medical imaging and document processing with minimal compute.",
